@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Async / RxJS";
}

<style>
.lesson-container { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding-bottom: 3rem; }
.lesson-intro { margin-bottom: 2rem; color: #8b949e; font-size: 1.1rem; }
.example-card { background: var(--card-bg, #21262d); border: 1px solid var(--border, #30363d); border-radius: 8px; padding: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; }
</style>

<div class="lesson-container">
  <h2>Async / RxJS Patterns</h2>
  <p class="lesson-intro">Angular relies heavily on RxJS for asynchronous operations (like HTTP requests, event streams).</p>

  <div class="example-card">
    <p style="color: #e6edf3;">In ASP.NET Core MVC, async operations are usually handled by <code>async/await</code> in C# controllers. On the client side, you can use JS <code>Promises</code> or native <code>async/await</code> instead of RxJS for typical scenarios.</p>
  </div>
</div>
